Wi-Fi-connected IoT devices are increasingly targeted by cyberattacks because they often have limited security features and are connected to home or enterprise networks.
One common attack vector is exploiting WPA2 vulnerabilities, such as the KRACK (Key Reinstallation Attack),
which allows attackers to manipulate the WPA2 handshake and potentially intercept or modify encrypted network traffic if devices are not patched.
Another threat is the evil twin attack, where an attacker creates a fake Wi-Fi access point that mimics a legitimate network.
If an ESP32 or another IoT device connects to this rogue access point, sensitive information may be exposed or communications intercepted.

To improve security, ESP32-based IoT devices should follow several best practices.
Using WPA3 instead of WPA2 provides stronger encryption and better protection against password-guessing attacks.
When connecting to cloud services, developers should use HTTPS/TLS and implement certificate pinning,
which verifies that the server's certificate matches a trusted certificate embedded in the device.
This helps prevent man-in-the-middle attacks. Devices should also use strong, unique Wi-Fi passwords, keep firmware updated,
disable unnecessary services, and securely store credentials using protected storage mechanisms where possible.

Hardcoding Wi-Fi passwords directly into source code is dangerous because anyone with access to the code repository or compiled firmware may extract these credentials.
If the code is accidentally shared on GitHub or another public platform, attackers can gain unauthorized access to the Wi-Fi network and compromise connected devices.
A safer approach is to store credentials in a separate configuration file (for example, config.h) 
that is excluded from version control using .gitignore, or to use secure provisioning and encrypted storage.

